sets.evidence: ALT, AST, ALP, and TBIL levels were lower and less disperse in non-severe cases. These levels increased and grew more disperse as the disease became more severe.
The dynamic changes in indicators suggested potential mechanisms of COVID-19-associated liver injury.
Among these liver enzymes, elevated AST was associated with the highest mortality risk.
Moreover, elevation of other enzymes and TBIL were also significantly associated with adverse outcomes of COVID-19 (Table 2 and Supporting Table S4-S5).
Male gender, systemic corticosteroids application, lymphocyte count decrease, neutrophil count increase, and fever were factors positively associated with elevated ALT levels (Table 3).
Use of antifungal drugs, lymphocyte count decrease, chronic liver disease, systemic corticosteroids use, and male gender were the leading factors positively associated with elevated AST levels
ALP levels were tightly associated with antifungal drug use, neutrophil counts increase, chronic liver disease, and male gender.
Antifungal, antiviral, systemic corticosteroids use, and platelet count reduction were main factors positively correlated with increased TBIL levels.
